    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Surprise! Debates May Matter. And Help Bush'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Surprise! Debates May Matter. And Help Bush'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27):</p>
        <p>While you report that the Commission on Presidential Debates is bipartisan, you don't mention that its rules make it nearly impossible for a third-party candidate to participate in debates, since a candidate must receive 15 percent support in national polls to participate. Indeed, debates sponsored by a bipartisan commission are antithetical to the free exchange of ideas that lies at the core of a vibrant democracy.</p>
        <p>The Federal Election Commission gives public campaign funds to any party whose candidate draws 5 percent of the vote. This standard should be sufficient for getting into the debates. Ralph Nader, the Green Party presidential candidate, looks set to meet the F.E.C. standard. But it looks as if he won't be heard in the debates, and our democracy will suffer for it.</p>
        <p>JONATHAN MASKIT  Columbus, Ohio, Aug. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
